Sure, here's a JavaScript function that takes an array of string values and randomizes the order of the elements in the array:

```
function shuffleArray(array) {
  for (let i = array.length - 1; i > 0; i--) {
    const j = Math.floor(Math.random() * (i + 1));
    [array[i], array[j]] = [array[j], array[i]];
  }
  return array;
}
```

To use this function, simply pass in an array of string values as an argument, like so:

```
const myArray = ['apple', 'banana', 'cherry', 'date', 'elderberry'];
const randomizedArray = shuffleArray(myArray);
console.log(randomizedArray);
```

This will output a randomized version of the original array to the console.
